ðŸ”¹ Step 2: Start and Enable the Service

		-sudo systemctl start fail2ban
		-sudo systemctl enable fail2ban
		
ðŸ”¹ Step 3: Create Local Jail Configuration
	We donâ€™t modify the original jail.conf, instead create a custom one:

		-sudo cp /etc/fail2ban/jail.conf /etc/fail2ban/jail.local
		
	-Now open the jail.local file for editing:
	
		-sudo nano /etc/fail2ban/jail.local

	-Inside, configure this section ðŸ‘‡ (search sshd protection):
	
		[sshd]
		enabled = true
		port = ssh
		backend = systemd
		maxretry = 3
		bantime = 600
		findtime = 300
		
ðŸ”¹ Step 4: Restart Fail2ban and check Status 

	-sudo systemctl restart fail2ban
	-sudo systemctl status fail2ban
	
Step 5: Check Fail2ban Status for SSH

	-sudo fail2ban-client status sshd
	
		-Youâ€™ll see something like:
		
			Status for the jail: sshd
